"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146470","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>Cabinet Office records show that the Department has not awarded a commercial contract to, or purchased digital services from Anomaly LLP or Anomaly UK London Ltd in the last six months.</p><p>Records of central Government contracts above £10,000 are published on Contracts Finder: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p><p> </p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-10-01T14:07:21.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146470/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146470/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146470/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-26","Cabinet Office: Anomaly","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether his Department has (a) awarded a commercial contract to and (b) purchased digital services from (i) Anomaly LLP and (ii) Anomaly UK London Ltd in the last six months.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","291341"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146471","Department for Education","false","2019-10-01","<p>The Department has not spent any money on the Getting Ready for Brexit campaign since 23 July 2019. No contracts have been awarded by the Department as a part of this campaign.</p><p>The Department is providing its own guidance to the education sectors that it serves via published information on GOV.UK, support through existing networks, and otherwise through the normal conduct of the day-to-day business of the Government, for which officials are aware of the need to uphold the values of the civil service code. All Departmental communications are subject to rigorous clearance processes.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-10-01T16:48:09.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146471/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146471/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146471/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-26","Department for Education: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what amount his Department has spent on the Getting Ready for Brexit campaign since 23 July 2019; which companies have been awarded contracts by his Department as part of the Getting Ready for Brexit campaign; whether (a) Ministers and (b) civil servants including special advisers declared any interests in relation to those contracts; and what steps he is taking to ensure that the civil service code values of transparency and impartiality are maintained through the effective governance of communications on the UK's departure from the EU.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","291342"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146472","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>Records of central Government contracts above £10,000 and information on how they are awarded are published on Contracts Finder: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Search</a></p><p> </p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-10-01T14:05:43.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146472/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146472/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146472/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-26","Government Departments: CDL Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what is (a) the nature of services purchased by the Government from CDL Group, (b) the value of the contract, (c) the length of the contract, (d) the process by which the contract was awarded and (e) whether any interests were declared by Ministers and civil servants, including special advisers, in relation to the award of the contract.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","291343"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146473","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-04","<p>The Prime Minister intends to request that the current session of Parliament be prorogued from the evening of Tuesday 8 October, with a Queen’s Speech on Monday 14 October.</p><p>These timings would mean Parliament is prorogued for the shortest time possible to enable all the necessary logistical preparations for a State Opening to be undertaken, including those done by the House Authorities.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-10-04T16:07:40.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146473/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146473/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146473/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-26","Prorogation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment he has made of the length of prorogation required in order for the Government to prepare for a Queen's speech.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","291405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146474","Department for International Development","false","2019-10-01","<p>DFID has been liaising closely with the Government of Pakistan’s National Disaster Management Authority (NDMA) since the earthquake struck on 24 September 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Key humanitarian partners, including UN agencies, met with the NDMA to discuss the response to the earthquake on Friday 27 September. The NDMA confirmed that the Government of Pakistan will not launch any formal appeal or request for National or International Assistance, but donors and agencies can provide assistance on a voluntary basis.</p><p> </p><p>DFID stands ready to respond and the Natural Disaster Consortium partners have pre-positioned supplies which can be deployed at short notice.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2019-10-01T15:39:08.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146474/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146474/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146474/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-26","Kashmir: Earthquakes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment he has made of the humanitarian situation in Kashmir following the earthquake on 24 September 2019.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","291406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146475","Department for International Development","false","2019-10-01","<p>We are extremely concerned that the Nigerian Army has closed the offices of Action against Hunger and Mercy Corps in North East Nigeria.</p><p> </p><p>NGOs in the North East of Nigeria, including Action Against Hunger and Mercy Corps, provide millions of people with crucial, life-saving assistance. When these organisations are forced to withdraw it has a huge impact on the lives of the most vulnerable. We have urged the Government of Nigeria to complete their investigations swiftly to resolve the dispute and to enable the uninterrupted delivery of humanitarian assistance. We must ensure unimpeded access for people in need in line with International Humanitarian Law.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2019-10-01T15:45:17.553Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146475/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146475/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146475/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-09-26","Nigeria: Non-governmental Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to reports of the army expelling international NGOs from Nigeria, what assessment he has made of the ability of humanitarian organisations to carry out their activities in Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","291407"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146476","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-01","<p>As set out in the Secretary of State’s Direction of 8 May and in the response to 275187, it was concluded, on this occasion, that it was reasonable for Government to protect Permitted Subcontractors who suffered losses as they relate to the collapse of Working Links and their Community Rehabilitation Companies. These organisations are directly involved in the delivery of vital frontline probation services. We have been very clear that this is a unique response to a unique and specific set of circumstances. This should not be viewed as setting a precedent for future scenarios.</p><p>Of the ten permitted subcontractors that the Authority agreed to make payments to as per the Ministerial Direction of 8 May, nine have been paid to date. The invoice from the remaining permitted subcontractor is currently being reviewed as part of our due diligence process. <br> <br>Contractors outside of the permitted subcontractor list should continue to pursue any financial claims through the Administrator. The Authority can assist in this process if required.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer",,"2019-10-01T09:55:20.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146476/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146476/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146476/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-09-26","Working Links: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what support he can provide to charities and other organisations who have not been paid money owed to them as a result of Working Links going into administration.","false","Biography information for Sarah Newton","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton","291408"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146477","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-10-01T08:49:50.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146477/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146477/answer","PQ291409 (1).pdf","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146477/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-26","Census: Sikhs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate his Department has made of the number of Sikhs who did not identify themselves as either religious or ethnically Sikh in the 2011 census.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","291409"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146478","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-01","<p>Routine scheduled repair and refitting of the two Queen Elizabeth Class (QEC) aircraft carriers, other than dry-docking, will be undertaken at Her Majesty's Naval Base Portsmouth.</p><p> </p><p>Plans for a long-term in-service support solution are under consideration as part of the Common Support Model for complex warships. Whilst no decisions have been made, we anticipate that dry-docking periods will be put out to competitive tender if the market for such work exists, in line with Departmental policy. The costs of dry docking QEC aircraft carriers have been benchmarked in competition to ensure value for money through negotiation with suppliers if no market for competition is forthcoming.</p><p> </p><p>It is currently too early for any formal engagement with industry on these matters, but the following dry-dock facilities in the UK are of a sufficient size to accommodate the Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers:</p><p> </p><p>Able UK, Seaton Port, Teeside; Babcock, Rosyth; Cammell Laird, Birkenhead; Cammell Laird, Greenock (Inchgreen); Harland and Wolff, Belfast.</p>","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Anne-Marie Trevelyan","290978 ; 290979","2019-10-01T13:52:54.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146478/answer","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146478/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146478/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-26","HMS Prince of Wales: Ports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which dry dock facilities in the UK are under consideration for future refits for the Prince of Wales aircraft carrier.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","291410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146479","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-10-01","<p>An assessment of the decision to use gross income to calculate child maintenance liabilities was carried out when we developed the 2012 statutory scheme.</p><p> </p><p>It is important that the rules used to calculate a child maintenance liability are applied consistently to avoid the complexities for clients that would result from applying different rules to different parts of the UK. The maintenance calculation is designed to be affordable for the non-resident parent, while still ensuring that they contribute a significant proportion of their income to support children they no longer live with.</p><p> </p><p>There is no evidence to suggest that parents are disproportionately affected by the decision to use gross income, because of where they reside in the UK.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-10-01T15:55:41.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146479/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146479/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-09-26","Children: Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 5 September 2019 to Question 285165 on Children: Maintenance, for what reasons she has not made an assessment of the effect on equality of calculating child maintenance liabilities using gross income due to different tax liabilities in the constituent parts of the UK.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","291411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146480","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-04","<p>On Friday 20 September the Department announced the operators who had been successful in applying to join the Freight Capacity framework, and also launched two Call Off mini-competitions to provide capacity for 31 October. We intend to award Call Off contracts to successful bidders by 12 October.</p><p> </p><p>It will be for suppliers on the framework to set out in their bids the ports, airports and rail terminals that they intend to use to meet the government’s capacity requirements.</p><p> </p><p>To support the flow of vital Category 1 goods, the Call Off mini-competitions did not include those ports and terminals that posed an unacceptable risk of disruption to the flow of critical ‘category 1’ goods, including medicines.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","291367","2019-10-04T12:44:36.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146480/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146480/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146480/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-26","Freight: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when the competition for contracts under the Freight Capacity Framework Agreement will be completed and the winning bidders announced.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","291366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146481","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-04","<p>On Friday 20 September the Department announced the operators who had been successful in applying to join the Freight Capacity framework, and also launched two Call Off mini-competitions to provide capacity for 31 October. We intend to award Call Off contracts to successful bidders by 12 October.</p><p> </p><p>It will be for suppliers on the framework to set out in their bids the ports, airports and rail terminals that they intend to use to meet the government’s capacity requirements.</p><p> </p><p>To support the flow of vital Category 1 goods, the Call Off mini-competitions did not include those ports and terminals that posed an unacceptable risk of disruption to the flow of critical ‘category 1’ goods, including medicines.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris","291366","2019-10-04T12:44:36.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146481/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146481/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-26","Freight","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which (a) ports, (b) airports and (c) rail freight terminals could provide additional freight capacity under the Freight Capacity Framework Agreement.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","291367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146482","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-02","<p>The Department is doing everything appropriate to prepare for the United Kingdom’s exit from the European Union. We want to reassure patients that our plans should ensure the supply of medicines and medical products, including those used in the treatment of haemophilia, when we leave the EU on 31 October.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, in partnership with the devolved administrations, has been working with trade bodies, product suppliers, and the health and care system across the UK to make detailed plans that should ensure continuation of the supply of medicines, to the whole of the UK and its Crown Dependencies.</p><p> </p><p>On 26 June, we wrote to suppliers of medicines to the UK from or via the EU or European Economic Area setting out our continuing multi-layered approach to support continuity of supply of medicines and medical products from 31 October.</p><p>Further details can be found at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/medicines-and-medical-products-supply-government-updates-no-deal-brexit-plans" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/medicines-and-medical-products-supply-government-updates-no-deal-brexit-plans</a></p><p>Ahead of 31 October, all necessary funding will be made available to support our preparations.</p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-02T14:12:28.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146482/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146482/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-26","Haemophilia: Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps he is taking to ensure that the supply of factor concentrates for haemophiliacs will not be affected in the event that the UK leaves the EU without a deal.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","291412"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146483","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-02","<p>The Secretary of State has had no discussions with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on extending the Cycle to Work scheme to include bus travel.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-02T15:51:54.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146483/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146483/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-26","Bus Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer on extending the Cycle to Work scheme to include bus travel.","false","Biography information for Luke Pollard","Plymouth, Sutton and Devonport","Luke Pollard","291413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146484","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-02","<p>Work on this is ongoing. On 1 July 2019, Ministers of the UK and Scottish Governments and the Leaders of the five councils of the Borderlands Partnership signed the ‘Heads of Terms’ for the £394.5 million Borderlands Inclusive Growth Deal. This includes up to £10 million joint funding with Scottish Government to assess the feasibility of extending the Borders Railway from Tweedbank to Carlisle.</p><p> </p><p>The full Heads of Terms document sets out further details of the projects being proposed and is available on the GOV.UK website at: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/816873/Borderlands_Growth_Deal_-_Heads_of_Terms_2019.pdf" target="_blank">https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/816873/Borderlands_Growth_Deal_-_Heads_of_Terms_2019.pdf</a></p><p> </p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-02T15:57:38.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146484/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146484/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-26","Borders Railway Line: Carlisle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to make an assessment of the feasibility of extending the Borders railway to Carlisle.","false","Biography information for John Lamont","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","John Lamont","291414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146485","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-02","<p>The Sheffield to Manchester corridor has recently seen an improvement which means that since 2018 there is an hourly Sheffield to Manchester Piccadilly service every day and two weekday trains per hour from New Mills Central to Manchester Piccadilly via Bredbury – one of these trains is a Hope Valley Sheffield service. We will be working with industry parties to deliver further improvements with the planned split of the Liverpool to Norwich East Midlands Railway service into a self-contained Liverpool to Nottingham service in 2021 and when the Hope Valley capacity improvement scheme is delivered thereafter.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-02T16:01:11.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146485/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146485/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-26","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to improve rail connectivity between South Yorkshire and Greater Manchester.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","291415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146486","Department for Transport","false","2019-10-02","<p>Network Rail have completed the single option design for the railway infrastructure scheme proposed in the Hope Valley and are working on plans to progress the work to the next stage ‘Decision to Deliver’. Network Rail have developed a procurement plan to deliver the scheme, and <em>expect to contact potential </em>suppliers shortly<em>.</em> They will be working with the train operators to assess the best way to deliver this scheme during control period 6 (2019-2024) with the least disruption to passengers.</p>","Daventry","Chris Heaton-Harris",,"2019-10-02T16:11:13.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146486/answer","Biography information for Chris Heaton-Harris","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146486/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-09-26","Manchester-Sheffield Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department has made on the capacity improvement scheme planned for the Hope Valley Line; and what recent discussions he has had with Network Rail to ensure that work is completed as quickly as possible.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","291416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146487","Department for Education","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Department is taking forward an ambitious programme of reform which will respect head teachers’ powers to use exclusion, while equipping schools to support children at risk of exclusion and ensuring excluded children continue to receive a good education. The Department has already begun engaging with stakeholders including schools and local authorities on these reforms.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government committed to establishing a practice programme that embeds effective partnership working between local authorities, schools, alternative provision, and other partners.</p><p> </p><p>This will better equip schools to intervene early for children at risk of exclusion and to ensure that the most effective provision is put in place for those who are excluded.</p><p>The Department will also re-write guidance on exclusions and behaviour to offer clearer, more consistent guidance to schools on managing behaviour, the use of in-school units, managed moves and the circumstances where it may be appropriate to use exclusion.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance will be published by summer 2020 and more details on the practice programme will be announced in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","291418 ; 291420","2019-10-07T15:57:00.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146487/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146487/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146487/answer/previousversion/137428","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-09-26","School Exclusions Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Timpson review of school exclusion: Government response, published in May 2019, what progress his Department has made on establishing the practice programme to embed effective partnership working to better equip schools to intervene early for children at risk of exclusion.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291417"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146488","Department for Education","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Department is taking forward an ambitious programme of reform which will respect head teachers’ powers to use exclusion, while equipping schools to support children at risk of exclusion and ensuring excluded children continue to receive a good education. The Department has already begun engaging with stakeholders including schools and local authorities on these reforms.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government committed to establishing a practice programme that embeds effective partnership working between local authorities, schools, alternative provision, and other partners.</p><p> </p><p>This will better equip schools to intervene early for children at risk of exclusion and to ensure that the most effective provision is put in place for those who are excluded.</p><p>The Department will also re-write guidance on exclusions and behaviour to offer clearer, more consistent guidance to schools on managing behaviour, the use of in-school units, managed moves and the circumstances where it may be appropriate to use exclusion.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance will be published by summer 2020 and more details on the practice programme will be announced in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","291417 ; 291420","2019-10-07T15:57:00.723Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146488/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146488/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146488/answer/previousversion/137447","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-09-26","School Exclusions Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Timpson review of school exclusion: Government response, published in May 2019, what progress his Department has made on providing guidance on the use of in-school units and managed moves; and what the timetable is for his Department's consultation on that guidance.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146489","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>​Since 2014, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) has handled over 131,000 new Consular assistance cases and issued more than 182,000 emergency travel documents to British nationals who have had their passports stolen, lost, damaged or were otherwise unavailable. The FCO has responded to over 1,800,000 Consular telephone enquiries over the same period.</p>","Pendle","Andrew Stephenson",,"2019-10-01T09:06:58.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146489/answer","Biography information for Andrew Stephenson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146489/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-26","Diplomatic Service: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many requests have been made for consular assistance by UK citizens since 2014.","false","Biography information for Hannah Bardell","Livingston","Hannah Bardell","291419"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146490","Department for Education","false","2019-10-07","<p>The Department is taking forward an ambitious programme of reform which will respect head teachers’ powers to use exclusion, while equipping schools to support children at risk of exclusion and ensuring excluded children continue to receive a good education. The Department has already begun engaging with stakeholders including schools and local authorities on these reforms.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, the Government committed to establishing a practice programme that embeds effective partnership working between local authorities, schools, alternative provision, and other partners.</p><p> </p><p>This will better equip schools to intervene early for children at risk of exclusion and to ensure that the most effective provision is put in place for those who are excluded.</p><p>The Department will also re-write guidance on exclusions and behaviour to offer clearer, more consistent guidance to schools on managing behaviour, the use of in-school units, managed moves and the circumstances where it may be appropriate to use exclusion.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance will be published by summer 2020 and more details on the practice programme will be announced in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","291417 ; 291418","2019-10-07T15:57:00.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146490/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146490/answer","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146490/answer/previousversion/137448","Biography information for Nick Gibb","60","Education","Education","2019-09-26","School Exclusions Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to the Timpson review of school exclusions, when his Department plans to issue updated guidance on school exclusions to schools.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291420"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146491","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-10-01","<p>Under current proposals the New and Replacement Obligation (NRO) will remain in place after 2024. The NRO requires energy suppliers to take all reasonable steps to install a smart meter where a meter is fitted for the first time, including in new build properties, or when an existing meter needs to be replaced. Under these proposals, consumers could choose not to have a smart meter. However, we expect the benefits of, amongst others, improved customer service, access to new products and services, and energy and bill savings will make smart meters the preferred choice for consumers.</p>","Spelthorne","Kwasi Kwarteng",,"2019-10-01T15:13:54.02Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146491/answer","Biography information for Kwasi  Kwarteng","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146491/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-09-26","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether customers will have the right to refuse the installation of smart meters in their homes after 2024.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","291286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146492","Home Office","false","2019-10-08","<p>Whether the UK leaves the EU on 31 October 2019 with or without a deal, the Government has announced that EEA and Swiss citizens will be able to continue to travel to the UK until the end of 2020 without needing a visa.</p><p>From January 2021 we will introduce a new points-based immigration system. This will prioritise the skills and contributions people can make to the UK, rather than where they come from.</p><p>In a no deal scenario, there will be a transitional period before the new immigration system commences in 2021. The Government announced the details of these temporary immigration arrangements on 4 September 2019 and they are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit</a>.</p><p>Law-abiding EEA and Swiss citizens moving to the UK after a no deal Brexit will still be able to live and work in the UK for a temporary period, but we will make it harder for serious criminals to enter the UK. Those new arrivals who wish to stay beyond the end of 2020 will need to apply for a UK immigration status. The Home Office will open a new immigration scheme – the European Temporary Leave to Remain Scheme – to provide a route to apply for this status. The online application process will be simple and free of charge. Subject to identity, security and criminality checks, successful applicants will be granted 36 months’ leave to remain in the UK. This will provide them with a bridge into the new immigration system.</p><p>EEA and Swiss citizens who are resident in the UK by exit on 31 October 2019 will remain eligible to apply for UK immigration status under the EU Settlement Scheme. They will have until at least 31 December 2020 to do so.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","291422 ; 291423","2019-10-08T15:05:21.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146492/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146492/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-26","Visas: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that visa-free travel is maintained between the UK and the EU for short visits to work in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146493","Home Office","false","2019-10-08","<p>Whether the UK leaves the EU on 31 October 2019 with or without a deal, the Government has announced that EEA and Swiss citizens will be able to continue to travel to the UK until the end of 2020 without needing a visa.</p><p>From January 2021 we will introduce a new points-based immigration system. This will prioritise the skills and contributions people can make to the UK, rather than where they come from.</p><p>In a no deal scenario, there will be a transitional period before the new immigration system commences in 2021. The Government announced the details of these temporary immigration arrangements on 4 September 2019 and they are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit</a>.</p><p>Law-abiding EEA and Swiss citizens moving to the UK after a no deal Brexit will still be able to live and work in the UK for a temporary period, but we will make it harder for serious criminals to enter the UK. Those new arrivals who wish to stay beyond the end of 2020 will need to apply for a UK immigration status. The Home Office will open a new immigration scheme – the European Temporary Leave to Remain Scheme – to provide a route to apply for this status. The online application process will be simple and free of charge. Subject to identity, security and criminality checks, successful applicants will be granted 36 months’ leave to remain in the UK. This will provide them with a bridge into the new immigration system.</p><p>EEA and Swiss citizens who are resident in the UK by exit on 31 October 2019 will remain eligible to apply for UK immigration status under the EU Settlement Scheme. They will have until at least 31 December 2020 to do so.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","291421 ; 291423","2019-10-08T15:05:21.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146493/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146493/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-26","Immigration: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether a new immigration system will be in place from 1 November 2019 for people working in the UK and not under visiting or settled status.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146494","Home Office","false","2019-10-08","<p>Whether the UK leaves the EU on 31 October 2019 with or without a deal, the Government has announced that EEA and Swiss citizens will be able to continue to travel to the UK until the end of 2020 without needing a visa.</p><p>From January 2021 we will introduce a new points-based immigration system. This will prioritise the skills and contributions people can make to the UK, rather than where they come from.</p><p>In a no deal scenario, there will be a transitional period before the new immigration system commences in 2021. The Government announced the details of these temporary immigration arrangements on 4 September 2019 and they are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/no-deal-immigration-arrangements-for-eu-citizens-moving-to-the-uk-after-brexit</a>.</p><p>Law-abiding EEA and Swiss citizens moving to the UK after a no deal Brexit will still be able to live and work in the UK for a temporary period, but we will make it harder for serious criminals to enter the UK. Those new arrivals who wish to stay beyond the end of 2020 will need to apply for a UK immigration status. The Home Office will open a new immigration scheme – the European Temporary Leave to Remain Scheme – to provide a route to apply for this status. The online application process will be simple and free of charge. Subject to identity, security and criminality checks, successful applicants will be granted 36 months’ leave to remain in the UK. This will provide them with a bridge into the new immigration system.</p><p>EEA and Swiss citizens who are resident in the UK by exit on 31 October 2019 will remain eligible to apply for UK immigration status under the EU Settlement Scheme. They will have until at least 31 December 2020 to do so.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","291421 ; 291422","2019-10-08T15:05:21.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146494/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146494/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-09-26","Immigration: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, whether there will be a transition immigration system in place from 1 November 2019 for people working in the UK and not under visiting or settled status.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146495","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-10-04","<p>The Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union has regular discussions with EU counterparts regarding preparations for the UK’s departure from the European Union.</p><p>Throughout this process the Government’s position has been clear; we want a positive future relationship that will support the growth of the creative industries in both the UK and the EU.</p><p>For British musicians resident in the EU before exit day, all Member States have now set out unilateral offers for resident UK nationals in the event of a no deal, and have drafted or enacted relevant legislation, which has been summarised on the European <a href="https://ec.europa.eu/info/brexit/brexit-preparedness/citizens-rights_en" target="_blank">Commission website</a>:</p><p>https://ec.europa.eu/info/brexit/brexit-preparedness/citizens-rights_en</p><p>After exit, if the UK leaves the EU with a deal, the existing EU rules will continue during the implementation period. This would allow UK nationals and EU citizens to visit and work in each other's territories as they do now from exit day until the end of the implementation period.</p><p>If the UK leaves the EU without a deal, UK nationals travelling to the EU to undertake paid work, including in the music industry, should check with the Embassy of the countries they plan to travel to for what kind of visa or permit, if any, they will need. Information about entry requirements for those intending to work or provide a service in an EU Member State is listed on our <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/providing-services-to-eea-and-efta-countries-after-eu-exit" target="_blank">advice pages for UK businesses</a> on gov.uk:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/providing-services-to-eea-and-efta-countries-after-eu-exit</p><p> </p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2019-10-04T10:09:06.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146495/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146495/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-09-26","Musicians: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with his EU counterparts on work permits for British musicians living and working in the EU on 1 November 2019.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291424"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146496","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-10-02","<p>When the UK leaves the EU on 31 October 2019, free movement as it currently stands will end. Musicians will need to check if they need a visa or work permit and meet any requirements for their profession to work in the EU country they’re visiting.</p><p> </p><p>Officials are meeting with the music industry to ensure that professionals in the sector are aware of Government guidance on EU Exit, and have time to prepare for changes at the border in the event the UK leaves without a Deal.</p>","Selby and Ainsty","Nigel Adams",,"2019-10-02T16:28:07.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146496/answer","Biography information for Nigel Adams","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146496/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-09-26","Musicians: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps she has taken to ensure that British musicians will be able to apply for work permits that will be valid from 1 November 2019 in the event that an agreement is not reached before the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","291425"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146497","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>We are following the serious situation in Kashmir closely. The continued use of detentions is worrying. We have raised our concerns with the Indian Government: the Prime Minister has discussed the situation with Prime Minister Modi and the Foreign Secretary has also discussed it with his counterpart Dr Jaishankar.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-10-01T15:47:08.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146497/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146497/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146497/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-26","Kashmir: Prisoners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has made representations to his Indian counterpart on reports that 13,000 boys have been detained in Kashmir since its autonomous status was revoked on 5 August 2019; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","291426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146498","Women and Equalities","false","2019-10-04","<p>The Government Equalities Office does not collect or hold information regarding spend across government on International Women’s Day. It is for individual departments to decide if and how to celebrate this day.</p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-10-04T13:08:06.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146498/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146498/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146498/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2019-09-26","International Women's Day","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how much the Government have spent on celebrations for International Women's day in each year since 2015.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","291337"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146499","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>We are following the situation in Kashmir closely and are in regular contact with both the Indian and Pakistani Governments. The Prime Minister has spoken to Prime Minister Modi and Prime Minister Imran Khan about the situation and the Foreign Secretary has also raised his concerns with his Indian counterpart Dr Jaishankar.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-10-01T15:52:43.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146499/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146499/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-26","Kashmir: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he has taken to work towards the de-escalation of tensions over the situation in Kashmir; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","291427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146500","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-04","<p>As Minister for the Cabinet Office, I have Ministerial responsibility for the Infected Blood Inquiry. I replied to the letter from the hon. Member for Kingston Upon Hull on 30 September, and have apologised to her for the time taken to reply to her letter to the Prime Minister of 1 August.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2019-10-04T15:42:46.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146500/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146500/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-26","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, for what reasons the Government has not responded to the letter of the hon. Member for Kingston Upon Hull North dated the 1 August 2019 on compensation for victims of the contaminated blood scandal.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","291428"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146501","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>The UK has played a leading role in diplomatic efforts, including bringing together key international actors to try to find a peaceful solution. On 26 September, the UK co-hosted a political event at the UN General Assembly to coordinate the international community’s support for the UN-led peace process and endorse the UN Special Envoy Martin Griffiths’ plan to begin wider political discussion.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-10-01T15:59:31.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146501/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146501/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-26","Yemen: Armed Conflict","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he had with his international counterparts on the situation in Yemen at the UN General Assembly.","false","Biography information for Gill Furniss","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Gill Furniss","291429"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146503","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-10-03","<p>The UK Ministry of Defence runs a bi-annual Human Security Advisers Course which educates UK and International personnel in the principles of UN Security Council Resolutions on Women, Peace and Security, Children and Armed Conflict, Human Trafficking and Protection of Civilians. The course also aims to train personnel in how best to implement these principles on operations. Since 2018, students from international militaries have included; Pakistan, Iraq, Malaysia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Ethiopia, Nigeria, Somalia, Canada, United States, Afghanistan and Bangladesh.</p><p>In December 2019, the UK will also provide a Human Security export course in Uruguay. This will provide clear guidance on how personnel can recognise, report and appropriately respond and refer children affected by armed conflict.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-10-03T14:25:07.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146503/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146503/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146503/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-09-26","Armed Conflict: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the mandate of the UN Special Representative for Children and Armed Conflict, created by the UN General Assembly in December 1996, what steps his Department is taking to help ensure that allied forces receive training on children affected by armed conflict.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","291357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146504","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-01","<p>There are no plans to alter the process for making judicial appointments. Our judges are selected following a rigorous, independent, merit based process which is key to maintaining the quality, integrity and independence of our world class judiciary.</p><p> </p>","Croydon South","Chris Philp","291431","2019-10-01T16:51:38.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146504/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146504/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146504/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-09-26","Judiciary: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans he has to reform the process for making judicial appointments, including to the Supreme Court.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","291430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146505","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-01","<p>There are no plans to alter the process for making judicial appointments. Our judges are selected following a rigorous, independent, merit based process which is key to maintaining the quality, integrity and independence of our world class judiciary.</p><p> </p>","Croydon South","Chris Philp","291430","2019-10-01T16:51:38.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146505/answer","Biography information for Chris Philp","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146505/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146505/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-09-26","Judges: Public Appointments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the Government's policy is on politically appointed judges.","false","Biography information for Stuart C. McDonald","Cumbernauld, Kilsyth and Kirkintilloch East","Stuart C. McDonald","291431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146506","Cabinet Office","false","2019-10-01","<p>The Government Chief Digital and Information Officer (GCDIO) will lead HMG’s 17,000 strong DDaT community and be responsible for shaping and delivering HMG’s innovation and transformation strategies, the Chief Data Officer will work with the GCDIO to deliver this agenda.</p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-10-01T13:06:38.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146506/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146506/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146506/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-09-26","Government Chief Digital Information Officer: Government Chief Data Officer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the working relationship will be between the Chief Digital Information Officer and the Chief Data Officer.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","291432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146507","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-10-03","<p>The Government has no plans to make such an assessment. As independent judicial office holders it is for coroners to determine which tests are made as part of their investigation. Coroners have the necessary powers to order post mortem examinations, including the testing by a pathologist for substances such as Gamma-hydroxybutyrate.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Aldridge-Brownhills","Wendy Morton",,"2019-10-03T14:46:04.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146507/answer","Biography information for Wendy Morton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146507/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146507/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-09-26","Post-mortems","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of testing for the use of Gamma-hydroxybutyrate in postmortems when the cause of death is unclear.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","291433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146508","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-10-03","<p>​The Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria provide a thorough risk assessment framework for regulating the export of arms and dual-use equipment from the UK. The Government will not grant an export licence if to do so would be inconsistent with the Consolidated Criteria, including if there is a clear risk that the equipment might be used for internal repression, or in the commission of serious violations of International Humanitarian Law.</p>","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher",,"2019-10-03T13:47:00.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146508/answer","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146508/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146508/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-09-26","Armed Conflict: Civilians","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that the perpetrators of attacks on civilians in conflict zones are not supplied with arms, material or financial services by the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","291358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146509","Treasury","false","2019-10-04","<p>In 2016, the then Chancellor set out in a letter to the Treasury Select Committee an estimate of the impact of the Apprenticeship Levy on the NHS Hospital and Community Health Service in England. This was estimated to be around £190m in 2017-18.</p><p> </p><p>It is not possible to determine accurately the total annual value of levy payments made by all NHS trusts. This is because HMRC administrative data does not enable NHS trusts and their associated PAYE schemes to be readily identified.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-10-04T12:31:28.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146509/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146509/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146509/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-09-26","NHS: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much funding the NHS has contributed to the Apprenticeship Levy since its introduction in 2017.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","291359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146511","Department for Education","false","2019-10-03","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p><p>As the NHS is made up of a large number of diverse employers, it is not possible to identify apprenticeship levy spend or expired funds for the NHS as a whole. Moreover, due to taxpayer confidentiality, we are unable to publish the amount that individual employers have contributed through the apprenticeship levy.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","291361","2019-10-03T20:51:20.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146511/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146511/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146511/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-09-26","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much Apprenticeship Levy funding was drawn down by the NHS on a monthly basis in the financial years (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19 and (c) 2019-20 to date.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","291360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146512","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-10-01","<p>NHS England advise that they do not expect the total funding for Halton and Warrington clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) to change if the two organisations are merged.</p><p>The CCG allocations for 2019/20 to 2021/22 were set on a firm basis, with the final two years being indicative. NHS England reserves the right to reopen allocations in some circumstances.</p><p>The circumstances under which allocations can be reopened are set out at Annex C of the NHS England Board Paper PB.31.01.2019/04. Which is available at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/04-pb-31-01-2019-ccg-allocations-board-paper.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/04-pb-31-01-2019-ccg-allocations-board-paper.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-10-01T15:36:40.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146512/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146512/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1146512/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-09-26","Department of Health and Social Care: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, when he plans to answer Question 287463 tabled on 5 September 2019 by the hon. Member for Halton.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","291237"
